"Forkel R., Knoche R.","Nested regional climate-chemistry simulations for central Europe",2007,"Comptes Rendus - Geoscience","339","11-12",,"734","746",,,10.1016/j.crte.2007.09.018,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-36049021865&partnerID=40&md5=15436a976b3aba3d2c968ea892598c3e","Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe, Institut für Meteorologie und Klimaforschung, IMK-IFU, Kreuzeckbahnstraße 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany","Forkel, R., Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe, Institut für Meteorologie und Klimaforschung, IMK-IFU, Kreuzeckbahnstraße 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany; Knoche, R., Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe, Institut für Meteorologie und Klimaforschung, IMK-IFU, Kreuzeckbahnstraße 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany","The potential impact of global climate change on regional meteorology and near-surface ozone concentrations in central Europe and the effect of model resolution on the simulated quantities were studied using a coupled climate-chemistry model. Nested simulations with a horizontal resolution of 60 km for Europe and 20 km for central Europe were performed for two time slices of about 10 years representing present-day and future climate conditions. The model results indicate that increased solar radiation due to decreased cloud cover, higher temperatures, and enhanced isoprene emissions promote the formation of tropospheric ozone in central Europe under future climate conditions. Depending on the region, the increase of the mean daily maximum ranges between 2 and 10 ppb and exceedances of the threshold of 60 ppb for the 8-hourly mean as well as the AOT40 index were found to increase considerably. General tendencies in the regional distributions of near-surface ozone were similar for 60- and 20-km resolutions. However, pronounced regional differences were found for some regions due to stronger smoothing of anthropogenic and biogenic emissions as well as flattened topography for the 60-km resolution. © 2007 Académie des sciences.","Central Europe; Europe; Global climate change; Nested regional climate-chemistry simulations; Ozone (near-surface concentrations); Regional meteorology","atmospheric chemistry; climate conditions; cloud cover; concentration (composition); global change; ozone; regional climate; simulation; solar radiation; Central Europe; Eurasia; Europe",,,,,,"Cohan, D.S., Hu, Y., Russell, A.R., Dependence of ozone sensitivity analysis on grid resolution (2006) Atmos. Environ., 40, pp. 125-135; Dameris, M., Grewe, V., Hein, R., Schnadt, C., Brühl, C., Steil, B., Assessment of the future development of the ozone layer (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett., 25, pp. 3579-3582; Ehhalt, D., Prather, M., Dentener, F., Derwent, R., Dlugokencky, E., Holland, E., Isaksen, I., Wang, M., Atmospheric Chemistry and Greenhouse Gases (2001) Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, pp. 241-287. , Houghton J.T., Ding Y., Griggs D.J., Noguer M., van der Linden P.J., Dai X., Maskell K., and Johnson C.A. (Eds), Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, UK and New York, USA; Forkel, R., Knoche, R., Regional climate change and its impact on photooxidant concentrations in southern Germany: Simulations with a coupled regional climate-chemistry model (2006) J. Geophys. Res., 111, pp. D12302. , 10.1029/2005JD006748; Friedrich, R., Wickert, B., Schwarz, U., Reis, S., Improvement and application of methodology and models to calculate multiscale high resolution emission data for Germany and Europe (2000) Genemis Annual Report 1999, pp. 28-33. , Midgley P.M. (Ed), EUROTRAC ISS, München; Geiger, H., Barnes, I., Benjan, I., Benter, T., Spittler, M., The tropospheric degradation of isoprene: an updated module for the regional chemistry mechanism (2003) Atmos. Environ., 37, pp. 1503-1519; Gillani, N.V., Pleim, J.E., Sub-grid-scale features of antropogenic emissions of NOx and VOC in the context of regional eulerian models (1996) Atmos. Environ., 30, p